07148nam a22009135i 9789814818865DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20192019si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898148188657 a10.1355/97898148188652doi  a(DE-B1597)546457  a(OCoLC)1136280415  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aHIS0170002bisacsh00aImagining Asia(s) :bNetworks, Actors, Sites /ced. by Andrea Acri, Sraman Mukherjee, Murari K. Jha, Kashshaf Ghani. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (438 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Contributors -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Conceptualizing the Region: Past and Present -- t1. Locating Asia, Arresting Asia: Grappling with “The Epistemology that Kills” -- t2. Imagining “Maritime Asia” -- t3. In Search of an Asian Vision: The Asian Relations Conference of 1947 -- tPart II. Conceptualizing Asia through the Prism of Europe -- t4. In Pursuit of Knowledge from Asia: François Valentijn on the Hindu Social Divisions in the Coromandel Region, c. Seventeenth–Eighteenth Century -- t5. British Romantic Poetics and the Idea of Asia -- tPart III. Networks of Knowledge Across the Indian Ocean -- t6. An Indian Ocean Ribāṭ: War and Religion in Sixteenth-Century Ponnāni, Malabar Coast -- t7. Travelling Spirits: Revisiting Melaka’s Keramat from the Indian Ocean -- tPart IV. Histories and Geographies of Pilgrimage in Asia -- t8. Transmissions, Translations, Reconstitutions: Revisiting Geographies of Buddha Relics in the Southern Asian Worlds -- t9. The Politics of Pilgrimage: Reception of Hajj among South Asian Muslims -- tPart V: Trans-Local Dynamics and Intra-Asian Connections across Space and Time -- t10. Sanskritic Buddhism as an Asian Universalism -- t11. Interconnectedness and Mobility in the Middle Ages/Nowadays: From Baghdad to Chang’an and from Istanbul to Tokyo -- t12. Connecting Networks and Orienting Space: Relocating Nguyen Cochinchina between East and Southeast Asia in the Sixteenth and Eighteenth Centuries -- t13. The Highlands of West Sumatra and their Maritime Trading Connections -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs a continent lying to the east of Europe, Asia has been malleable to different spatial and temporal imaginations and politics. Recent scholarship has highlighted how the seemingly self-contained regional configurations of West and Central Asia, South and Southeast Asia, and East Asia carved by the Area Studies paradigm reflect changing (geo)political and economic interests than historical or cultural roots. This volume advances the question as to what Asia is, and as to whether there existed one or many Asia(s). It seeks to explore Asian societies as interconnected formations through trajectories/networks of circulation of people, ideas, and objects in the longue durée. Moving beyond the divides of Area Studies scholarship and the arbitrary borders set by late colonial empires and the rise of post-colonial nation-states, this volume maps critically the configuration of contact zones in which mobile bodies, minds, and cultures interact to foster new images, identities, and imaginations of Asia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 4aAsian History. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh1 aAcri, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAcri, Andrea, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBroilo, Federica A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhani, Kashshaf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhani, Kashshaf, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJha